'''Jonathan Lazare Alperin''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|l|p|ər|ɪ|n}}; born 1937) is an [[Americans|American]] [[mathematician]] specializing in the area of [[algebra]] known as [[group theory]]. He is notable for his work in group theory which has been cited over 500 times according to the [[Mathematical Reviews]].  The [[Alperin–Brauer–Gorenstein theorem]] is named after him.

==Biography==
Alperin attended school at [[Princeton University]] and wrote his Ph.D. dissertation in 1961 "''On a Special Class of Regular p-Groups''" under the direction of [[Graham Higman]].  He was awarded a [[Guggenheim Fellowship]] in 1974.  He has several times (1969, 1979, and 1983) been a visiting scholar at the [[Institute for Advanced Study]].<ref>[http://www.ias.edu/people/cos/frontpage?page=2 Institute for Advanced Study: A Community of Scholars] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106144316/http://www.ias.edu/people/cos/frontpage?page=2 |date=2013-01-06 }}</ref> In 2012 he became a fellow of the [[American Mathematical Society]].<ref>[http://www.ams.org/profession/fellows-list List of Fellows of the American Mathematical Society], retrieved 2012-11-03.</ref>

Alperin is a professor at the [[University of Chicago]] where he has had 22 students and 30 [[Mathematics Genealogy Project|descendants]]. He has published over 60
papers and his work has been cited over 500 times.

He is also known for his conjecture, {{harv|Alperin|1987}}, a topic of current research in [[modular representation theory]], and for his work on the local control of fusion, {{harv|Alperin|1967}}, part of [[P-group#Local control|local group theory]].  In {{harv|Alperin|1970}}, the [[Alperin–Brauer–Gorenstein theorem]] was proven, giving the classification of [[finite simple group]]s with [[Quasidihedral group|quasi-dihedral]] [[Sylow p-subgroup|Sylow 2-subgroups]].

